  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a strong consensus that money laundering is against the law in virtually every country around the world. Money laundering is the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). This practice is universally recognized as a serious crime because it enables criminals to profit from illegal activities such as drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, and terrorism, while also undermining the integrity of financial systems.\n\n### Key Points:\n1. **International Agreements**: Money laundering is addressed in international agreements such as the **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances** (1988) and the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** recommendations, which set global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n2. **National Laws**: Most countries have enacted laws criminalizing money laundering. For example:\n   - In the **United States**, the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Patriot Act** establish anti-money laundering (AML) regulations.\n   - In the **European Union**, the **Anti-Money Laundering Directives** (AMLD) provide a legal framework for member states.\n   - Other countries, such as **China**, **India**, and **Brazil**, also have robust AML laws.\n\n3. **Penalties**: Money laundering offenses typically carry severe penalties, including hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment.\n\n4. **Financial Institutions**: Banks and other financial institutions are required to implement AML measures, such as customer due diligence, transaction monitoring, and reporting suspicious activities.\n\n### Conclusion:\nMoney laundering is unequivocally illegal and universally condemned. Efforts to combat it involve international cooperation, stringent national laws, and proactive measures by financial institutions.",
